'''Naphthalocyanine''' is a derivative of [[phthalocyanine]] used as a component in the development of [[IBM]]'s [[molecular logic gate|single-molecule logic switch]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Liljeroth | first1 = P. | last2 = Repp | first2 = J. | last3 = Meyer | first3 = G. | doi = 10.1126/science.1144366 | title = Current-Induced Hydrogen Tautomerization and Conductance Switching of Naphthalocyanine Molecules | journal = Science | volume = 317 | issue = 5842 | pages = 1203–1206 | year = 2007 | pmid =  17761878| pmc = }}</ref>

It was used to show the first images of [[charge distribution]] over a single molecule in November 2011.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Mohn | first1 = F. | last2 = Gross | first2 = L. | last3 = Moll | first3 = N. | last4 = Meyer | first4 = G. | title = Imaging the charge distribution within a single molecule | doi = 10.1038/NNANO.2012.20 | journal = Nature Nanotechnology | year = 2012 | pmid =  | pmc = }} </ref><ref name='physorg'> {{cite news | title = Scientists image the charge distribution within a single molecule for the first time | date = 2012-02-27 | url = http://www.physorg.com/news/2012-02-scientists-image-molecule.html | work = Physorg.com | accessdate = 2012-02-27}}</ref>

Its derivatives may also have uses in [[photodynamic cancer treatment]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Shopova | first1 = M. | last2 = Woehrle | first2 = D. | last3 = Mantareva | first3 = V. | last4 = Mueller | first4 = S. | title = Naphthalocyanine Complexes as Potential Photosensitizers for Photodynamic Therapy of Tumors | doi = 10.1117/1.429930 | journal = Journal of Biomedical Optics | volume = 4 | issue = 3 | pages = 276 | year = 1999 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>

