The West Baltimore Innovation Village District is a neighborhood district of Baltimore City that will specialize in attracting [[Startup company|startup companies]] and other employers to West Baltimore. Following the [[Death of Freddie Gray]] and the subsequent [[2015 Baltimore protests]], government leaders decided to launch the innovation district as a way to attract redevelopment and revitalization to the areas hardest hit by the protests. The district includes the neighborhoods of [[Mondawmin, Baltimore|Mondawmin]], [[Coppin Heights, Baltimore|Coppin Heights]], [[Penn-North, Baltimore|Penn-North]], [[Reservoir Hill, Baltimore|Reservoir Hill]] and [[Bolton Hill, Baltimore|Bolton Hill]].<ref>http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2016/01/18/innovation-village-a-plan-to-revitalize-west.html#i2</ref>
==Background== Efforts to form the district originated from the community organization known as the Mount Royal Community Development Corporation (MRCDC).<ref>http://www.innovatebaltimore.org/</ref> Similar innovation districts have been formed in neighborhoods like [[University City, Philadelphia|University City]] in [[Philadelphia]] and the [[South Boston|South Boston Seaport District]].<ref>http://technical.ly/baltimore/2016/01/18/meet-group-neighbors-spearheading-west-baltimores-innovation-district/</ref> The West Baltimore Innovation District neighbors the nearby [[Station North Arts and Entertainment District]] and includes access to numerous forms of transportation including the [[Baltimore Metro Subway]] and [[Baltimore Light Rail]].
